At 8:05 that was a big question I have been trying to get an answer to for nearly three weeks. ‘After a respiratory Illness, When do you go back?’

I had an upper respiratory infection, (was down for two weeks and needed an inhaler to breath properly) but tests were not available. I work for an essential company, but they do not want me back unless there is some sort of messaging from the CDC, a negative test, or a doctors note saying that I will not infect everyone.

I have been symptom free for 7 days tomorrow, I feel great. I have been working out again, and my temperature has been normal, I’ve been monitoring.

At what point do I go back without being a risk to my coworkers? Where can I find that out? It was a little unclear.

At 8:05 that was a big question I have been trying to get an answer to for nearly three weeks.  ‘After a respiratory Illness, When do you go back?’

I had an upper respiratory infection, (was down for two weeks and needed an inhaler to breath properly) but tests were not available.  I work for an essential company, but they do not want me back unless there is some sort of messaging from the CDC, a negative test,  or a doctors note saying that I will not infect everyone.  

I have been symptom free for 7 days tomorrow, I feel great.  I have been working out again, and my temperature has been normal, I’ve been monitoring.  
 
At what point do I go back without being a risk to my coworkers?  Where can I find that out?  It was a little unclear.
